name: Amsterdam
description_text: Amsterdam is the official capital and most populous city of the Netherlands; with a population of 872,680 within the city proper, 1,380,872 in the urban area, and 2,410,960 in the metropolitan area. Found within the province of North Holland, Amsterdam is colloquially referred to as the "Venice of the North", attributed by the large number of canals which form a UNESCO World Heritage Site. |  | Amsterdam's name derives from Amstelredamme, indicative of the city's origin around a dam in the river Amstel. Originating as a small fishing village in the late 12th century, Amsterdam became one of the most important ports in the world in the Dutch Golden Age of the 17th century and became the leading centre for finance and trade. In the 19th and 20th centuries, the city expanded, and many new neighbourhoods and suburbs were planned and built.

name: Dam Square
description_text: The central square of Amsterdam got its name from its original purpose. Before there was a square, there was a real dam on the Amstel river. Today though it is an important national square where many events are organised during the year (Christmas celebrations, various fairs but also demonstrations and meetings etc.).  |  | There is a stunning National Monument located on the square that commemorates the victims of World War II. It was installed there in 1956 and the Remembrance of the Dead ceremony is held there every year.  |  | There are also several important buildings that are worth noticing located by the square – the 15th century Nieuwe Kerk (New Church), the imposing Royal Palace or the popular Madame Tussauds Wax Museum.

name: Zeeburgereiland
description_text: The Zeeburgereiland is a triangular island on the east side of Amsterdam, in the Dutch province of North Holland. It lies between the Oranjesluizen and the Diemerzeedijk and on the east is bordered by the IJ. Formerly an industrial area, the island is being redeveloped as part of the IJburg new neighbourhood. It is crossed by the A10 motorway and, since 2005, the IJ Tram line of the Amsterdam Tram system.

name: Vuurtoreneiland
description_text: Vuurtoreneiland is a small island in the IJmeer, Netherlands, just off the coast of Durgerdam. The island's main function is as a base for a lighthouse; a military fort on the island was abandoned in the 1930s.

name: Red Light District
description_text: The biggest and oldest of Amsterdam red light areas is not known only for prostitution. There are also many bars, clubs, coffee shops, sex shops and even sex museums located there. |  | The place got its name from the red neon lights and lamps that are used in most windows behind which there are individual sex workers offering their services. Do not try to take pictures of the women, though, it is strictly forbidden.  |  | The existence of the red light districts in Amsterdam dates back to the 14th century. For some time throughout its existence, married and religious men were banned from entering the De Wallen area. Today, it is one of Amsterdam’s popular attractions. |  | The lively nightlife goes hand in hand with the nature of the area. There are many clubs, pubs and bars that you can visit and have fun all night. Therefore the best time for visiting the district, if you wish to see it lit up and alive, is during the evening or at night.

name: Flower Market
description_text: The only floating flower market in the world, located on the Singel canal, supplies flowers to the whole centre of Amsterdam. There are several florist's shops where you can find not only the iconic Dutch tulips but other flowers as well. The market was established in the second half of the 19th century. Apart from the flowers, you can also get some gardening supplies or flower bulbs here. |  | It is a great place to visit not only for those with green fingers. Everyone will appreciate the colorful sight which is a living reminder of the times when the flowers were brought to the city exclusively by boats.

name: Royal Palace of Amsterdam
tags: Historic House Museum|Dutch Golden Age|Royal Palace|Baroque Architecture|Royal Residence|Palace|Castle
opening_hours_note: Most of the year, the Royal Palace is open to the public as well as providing guided tours. For more information visit the official website.
admission: Adults: €10 | CJP/CKV, Students: €9 | Children (under 18): free
description_text: The classicist palace located on the Dam Square began its life in the 17th century as a city hall. Its construction started in 1648 and the city hall was opened for the first time in 1655. During the reign of Louis Napoleon, it was turned into the royal palace. Nowadays, it is one of the three palaces that belong to the royal family. |  | If you want to avoid queuing, you can buy your tour tickets online. When entering the palace be prepared for security checks. Bags and purses must be left in the cloakroom before entering the palace.  |  | Also, since it is a royal palace it is closed for public on days when there are some official diplomatic events hosted or on royal family-related days (e.g. weddings, jubilees etc.). Therefore you might want to consult the official website before your visit.

name: Van Gogh Museum
tags: 360° Content|National Museum|Monet|Biographical Museum|Modern Art|Van Gogh|Museum|Amsterdam Holland Pass|Édouard Manet|Art|Auguste Rodin|Paul Gauguin|I Amsterdam City Card|Art Museum|Art Gallery|Van Gogh Museum|Wheelchair Accessible|Toulouse-Lautrec
opening_hours_note: Opening hours vary depending on the season, please check the official website for more information. | Last admission is 30 min before closing time. |  | Tip: visit the museum between 9 am and 11 am or after 3 pm as the busiest times are between 11 am and 3 pm.
admission: Adults: €19 | Children (under 18): free |  | It is recommended to purchase your tickets online in advance.
description_text: If you want to see the largest collection of Van Gogh’s paintings, then you must visit this museum. Not only does it contain 200 of his paintings and almost 500 drawings, but it also focuses on the life of this remarkable artist.  |  | Moreover, the museum also houses artworks of Van Gogh’s contemporaries -  Auguste Rodin,  Paul Gauguin, Édouard Manet, Claude Monet and many more.  |  | As for photography and filming, you are only allowed to use your camera in the specially designated areas including the Entrance Hall and museum’s special treats for the selfie lovers – the ‘selfie walls’. |  | Note that you must leave your backpacks and your umbrellas in the cloakroom. However, you cannot store any larger items in the cloakroom so please leave them in your hotel or in other luggage storage service. |  | The nearest tram stop is Van Baerlestraat, lines 2 or 5.

name: Anne Frank House
tags: 360° Content|Historic House Museum|Literary Museum|Biographical Museum|Holocaust|Anne Frank|Museum|Paid
opening_hours_raw: Nov 01-Mar 31 Mo-Fr,Su 09:00-19:00 "Online tickets only"; Nov 01-Mar 31 Sa 09:00-22:00 "Online tickets only"; Apr 01-Oct 31 Mo-Su 09:00-22:00 "Online tickets only"
opening_hours_note: For exceptions to the opening times, please check the official website.
admission: Adults: €10 | Children (10-17): €5 | Children (0-9): free | +0.50€ booking fee |  | The Anne Frank House can only be visited with a ticket bought online for a specific time slot.
description_text: The museum is devoted to the memory of Anne Frank, a very young German diarist, who was hiding in the secret room of this house during World War II.  |  | The museum was opened in 1960. Today, it is one of the most popular places to visit in Amsterdam. The museum (using - among others - photographs of Anne and bits of her diary) tells the story of the Nazi persecution that Anne (and the Jews in general) faced during World War II. The museum exhibitions are presented in an educative yet very interesting form.  |  | Due to its popularity, this museum is a busy place. You might want to consider buying your tickets online in order to avoid the long ticket queues that may take up more than an hour.

name: Canals of Amsterdam
description_text: This interconnected web of canals, in total about a hundred kilometres long, going through the city centre inspired Amsterdam’s nickname - “Venice of the North”.  |  | The main canals were constructed in the 17th century and the whole area coming from that age is on the UNESCO World Heritage List (since 2010). |  | The canals, crossed by roughly 1500 bridges, can be admired both from the shore (where you can enjoy the view of the canals with many little boats) or from the water (during a canal tour). The tours definitely offer a unique sight of the city and an unforgettable experience.

name: Vondelpark
description_text: A great place to visit if you wish to get some rest outdoors during a (sometimes rather hectic) day of sightseeing. It is a wonderful place for cyclists, in-line skaters or joggers. You can also have a picnic there or just sit on a bench and admire the English-styled greenery.  |  | The park was opened in 1867 and has been popular among the locals and the tourists ever since. The park even includes an open-air theatre with free entrance (though some small donations are expected). There is also a statue by Pablo Picasso (called The Fish) installed in the park.

name: Rijksmuseum
tags: Goya|Art Museum|Albrecht Dürer|Vermeer|Rembrandt|Dutch Art|Art Gallery|Historical|I Amsterdam City Card|Museum|History Museum|Amsterdam Holland Pass|Wheelchair Accessible|Asian Art|National Gallery|Rubens|Classic Art|Hieronymus Bosch|Monet|El Greco|Anthony van Dyck|Heritage
opening_hours_note: (Ticket desk closes at 4:30 pm)
admission: Adults: €20 | Children (under 18): Free |  | Buy tickets online to save €1.
description_text: This museum focuses on Dutch art, especially paintings, drawings and sculptures. The artworks on display range from those as old as the Middle Ages up to those from the 20th century. The crown jewels of the museum's large collection are a number of paintings by Rembrandt and Vermeer as well as the famous auto-portrait by Van Gogh. |  | The museum also has a restaurant and a café, as well as a cloakroom, where you can leave your luggage free of charge. This comes in handy since it is forbidden to carry bags larger than A4 inside the museum itself. |  | When visiting, expect an approximately 30 minutes-long wait in line for tickets. If you wish to avoid it, either come early in the morning, late in the afternoon or pre-purchase a ticket online.

name: Old Church
tags: 360° Content|Amsterdam Holland Pass|I Amsterdam City Card|Place of Worship|Protestant|Exhibition Hall|Wheelchair Accessible|Christian|Church|Art
opening_hours_note: Last admission 15 min before closing.
admission: Adults: €15 | Students: €10 | Children (under 13): €2
description_text: One of the oldest buildings in Amsterdam (built in 1306), located in the famous Red Light District. The close proximity of such an imposing religious building and the many bars and brothels surrounding it creates an interesting contrast.  |  | Nowadays, the church hosts not only religious events but cultural ones as well. Many concerts and prestigious ceremonies are organized there every year.  |  | It is not just a church but also a burial site. Many important residents of Amsterdam are buried under the building and you can see their tombstones on the floor of the church. Among those buried, there is, for example, Rembrandt’s wife, or several regents of Amsterdam. |  | You can also climb the church tower (as a part of the guided tour) and enjoy the beautiful view of the city. However, be prepared for the narrow steps because there are no lifts.  |  | You can buy your tickets online if you want to avoid the queues.

name: Rembrandt Square
description_text: Conveniently placed close to the centre of Amsterdam, this square is a major nightlife spot. It shares its name with the famous painter, Rembrandt van Rijn, who lived and worked in Amsterdam and had a house nearby the square. And although Rembrandt himself may be gone, a statue of him still stands here as a reminder. |  | Formerly a butter market, today the square offers its visitors a pleasant stop in one of its many cafés during the day and a place to unwind in one of the numerous bars and clubs during the night. |  | If you visit during the weekend, you may find a flea market or a food market here. The square is within walking distance of other popular sights and there is a direct connection by tram to it, too.

name: Westerkerk
description_text: The Western Church is a Renaissance Protestant church in Amsterdam. Its construction started in 1620 and it was finished in 1631. Its tower is the tallest church tower in the city.  |  | It is also the burial place of Rembrandt van Rijn, the famous Dutch Baroque painter and printmaker, but the exact location of his tomb remains unknown. |  | Anne Frank mentions the church and its tower many times in her diary. This comes as no surprise since the house where she lived is located near the Westerkerk. |  | In 1966 there was a royal wedding in the church – Princess Beatrix and Prince Claus von Amsberg got married there. |  | If you plan to visit the church, please bear in mind that services are still being held here and that it is a place of silence. The nearest tram station is Westermarkt (lines 13, 14 and 17).

name: Amsterdam Centraal Railway Station
opening_hours_note: Tourist office: | Mon - Sat: 9 am - 5 pm | Sun: 9 am - 4 pm |  | Information service on public transport & tickets: | Mon - Fri: 7 am - 9 pm | Sat: 8 am - 9 pm | Sun: 9 am - 9 pm
description_text: The largest railway station in Amsterdam is one of the gates to the city. It was opened in 1889 and the crowds of onlookers were so curious that they did not mind being charged money for the chance of looking at the building (only during the first days after its opening). Today, the entrance is free of charge but the place is still very busy because it is the focal point of Amsterdam's transport.  |  | All public transport is centred around the Centraal Station, so you can get there (or from there) by various means of transport (trams, buses, metro). Inside, the station is clean and full of little shops where you can get what you need for your journey (snacks, newspapers, books etc.). |  | If you want to avoid the daily to and from rushing crowds of commuters, look at the main building just from the outside. Its most imposing feature for the tourists is definitely the exterior beauty of the building (and not so much its interiors).

name: Begijnhof
opening_hours_note: Chapel: | Mon: 1 pm - 6:30 pm | Tue - Fri: 9 am - 6:30 pm | Sat, Sun: 9 am - 6 pm |  | The Beguinage is in private possession and is not a public ground. It is also a place of silence.
admission: Free entry.
description_text: The only inner court in Amsterdam with origins dating back to the Middle Ages. It is estimated that it was built by the end of the 14th century. It used to be a home to the beguines (religious women). Today it is a beautiful place of peace and quiet in the very heart of Amsterdam.  |  | You can find there the tall houses which are so typical for Amsterdam but also the oldest wooden house (one of the two still standing) in Amsterdam. |  | During most of its existence, Begijnhof was surrounded by the canals from all sides with only one entrance. Now, there are several entrances (e.g. from the Spui square).  |  | If you decide to visit the place, bear in mind that it is private property and you should behave quietly and respectfully. |  | You can get here by trams 4, 9, 14 and 24, tram station Spui.

name: Waterlooplein Market
description_text: This plaza, named after the battle which put a stop to emperor Napoleon's ambitions, wakes up every morning to the sounds of the oldest flea market in the Netherlands. Visitors browsing through the stalls can find anything here: from books to clothes or gems. |  | The market first opened here in 1882. It was mainly operated by Jewish merchants, who were forced to move here from the surrounding streets. Due to this, it used to have a peculiarity: it didn't close on Sunday but on Saturday, which is the day of the Jewish Sabbath. It nearly disappeared after the Nazis overtook the Netherlands. |  | Today, the market is open again and follows the usual opening schedule, closing on Sundays only. You can get here by exiting at the Waterlooplein stop of the metro or the tram. There is also a parking garage nearby.

name: Heineken Experience
tags: Amsterdam Holland Pass|Beer Museum|Brewery|Wheelchair Accessible|Museum|I Amsterdam City Card
opening_hours_note: Dec 24, 31: open until 4 pm |  | During July and August, weekend times apply.
admission: Adults: €21 | Children (12-17): €17.50 | Children (under 11): free |  | When booking online you get a €3 discount.
description_text: This is a must-see for all beer lovers. Come here to find out more about the production of liquid bread and get a complimentary drink or two at the bar. Although the brewery is not active anymore, it still provides detailed tours on how beer is made, which ingredients go in it and how to drink it properly.  |  | The staff is well-educated and gives you all the information you need or want, considering this famous brand. You will get to see machines previously used to brew this beer, photos and a well-preserved interior. |  | You can get here by trams 16, 24 and 25, station Stadhouderskade, or by 7 and 10, station Weteringcircuit.

name: Amsterdam Museum
tags: History Museum|Amsterdam Holland Pass|Wheelchair Accessible|Historical|Museum|I Amsterdam City Card
address: Kalverstraat 92 or Sint Luciënsteeg 27,  | 1012 RM Amsterdam, The Netherlands
opening_hours_note: Special opening times: | Jan 1: noon - 5 pm | Dec 5, 24 and 31: 10 am - 4 pm | Closed on Apr 27 and Dec 25.
admission: Adults: €15 | Children (0-17): free
description_text: Established in 1926 and relocated to its current location in 1975 – a 16th-century house that used to serve as a city orphanage. The artefacts of the original orphanage equipment are included in the museum exhibitions.  |  | The museum introduces its visitors to the history of Amsterdam from its creation to the present day. It explains to the visitors how the city was built on a marsh and how it developed into what it is today. The multimedia exhibitions include lots of engaging of the visitors so it is a good place for families with children. |  | There are new exhibitions added every now and then so be sure to check the official website before your visit so you would not miss anything. You can also buy your tickets online in advance through the official website. |  | You can get here from the Centraal Station, or if you don't want to walk that far, you can also choose to come here by trams 1, 2, 4, 5, 9, 14 and 16, the nearest stop is Spui.

name: The Smallest House In Amsterdam
opening_hours_note: On Monday and Sunday is the Smallest House in Amsterdam open by appointment.
description_text: Having the surface of only 9 square metres, this house can easily be overlooked. Despite this, it's one of the most photographed buildings in The Netherlands. If you come inside, you will be greeted by the amazing smell of various types of tea. Come here and have a cup or two while enjoying the inside, which resembles a real-life doll house.

name: Leidseplein Square
description_text: Leidseplein, or also Leiden Square, is the ideal place to enjoy a night out in Amsterdam. This spacious square is packed with bars and clubs and it is a popular nightlife hub both among the tourists and the locals. You won’t regret if you visit it during the day either - the square is full of restaurants offering various types of food, as well as plenty of coffee shops, and it bustles with life. |  | The square is located in the southern part of the city centre, so it is easy to reach both by foot and by bike, and you can find many other attractions close by. There are also plenty of stops for public transport all around the place since several tram lines intersect directly on the square.

name: Pancakes Amsterdam
description_text: A small shop in Amsterdam which sells all kinds and flavours of pancakes, a dish that originated in the Netherlands and has become one of the most iconic foods of the country. |   | The store, opened in 2007, can be found within walking distance of the Amsterdam's central square, on Berenstraat, one of the popular Nine Streets.  |  | Inside, you will find true pancake heaven. The shop sells pancakes done in either American or traditional Dutch style and you can order one of more than 15 varieties of pancakes, such as a pancake with smoked salmon, or apple and calvados pancake. The store also offers gluten-free and dairy-free pancakes.

name: In de Wildeman
description_text: If you are a fan of beer, this place is a must visit. It is located in a building that dates back to the 17th century and used to be a distillery. It serves more than 250 different bottled beers and 18 beers on tap.  |  | Whether you like the local beers (Dutch, Belgian) or you prefer the English beers or the German ones, you will find them all there. Even the American beers are served there. In case you do not like beer at all, there are even bottled ciders on the menu. |  | The place has a warm, rustic atmosphere despite being located in the city centre. If you want to escape the crowds of tourists for a moment or have a rest after a long day of sightseeing, you should consider visiting this beautiful bar. |  | The nearest tram station is Nieuwezijds Kolk, lines 1, 2, 5, 13 and 17.

name: Basilica of Saint Nicholas
tags: Place of Worship|Roman Catholic|Religious Art|Catholic|Dome|Neo-Baroque Architecture|Basilica|Budget-Friendly|Church|Neo-Renaissance Architecture|Christian|Mural|Free
description_text: Dwelling in the very heart of Amsterdam, this Catholic masterpiece is a sight to behold. It was built around the year 1887 using neo-Baroque and neo-Renaissance elements, and its status was elevated to Basilica in 2012.  |  | There is a beautiful rose window (circular window, usually divided with other materials into various patterns) between the towers. Aside from religious murals on the inside walls of the basilica, this building also exhibits the crown of Maximilian I.  |  | There are still frequent masses (even in English), that you can attend and experience the serenity while practising your faith. You can also come here to confess in English or Dutch. |  | The Basilica is a 2-minute walk away from the bus stop Prins Hendrikkade, lines 32-35, 301, 304, 306-308, 312- 316 and 319. Do not forget to take your camera with you, photos without flash are permitted, and you will have a memory to take home with you. All phones need to be on silent while inside the building, and there are no sightseeing tours allowed during services.
media_square_attribution: {"title":"The Church of St Nicholas in Amsterdam.","title_url":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:The_Church_of_St_Nicholas.jpg","author":"Swimmerguy269","author_url":"http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/User:Swimmerguy269","other":null,"license":"CC BY-SA 3.0","license_url":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0"}

name: Jordaan District
description_text: Originally a poor district, this neighbourhood nowadays houses numerous art galleries, shops and restaurants in its streets. It is also a great place to just take a walk in. |  | Its development started during the 17th century by the construction of housing facilities for the working class. Do not expect to find any decrepit houses here today, though. Jordaan has become one of the trendiest and most famous Amsterdam districts.  |  | Despite its popularity, the district is also quiet and calm. It is a lot less crowded than the city center. You can easily find an empty spot in one of the narrow streets and just enjoy yourself in peace here.  |  | The charming banks of canals offer great spots for walks or relaxation with many colorful pubs and restaurants near them. Some of the pubs will let you take your drinks all the way to the canals.  |  | Outside canals and shops, do not miss Jordaan's outdoor markets with differently themed days. There is a flea market on Mondays and a farmers‘ market on Saturdays. In September, the Jordaan Festival takes place here with plenty of beer and Dutch folk music.
media_portrait_attribution: {"title":"Rijksmonumenten in Amsterdam-Jordaan, Brouwersgracht 641, Pakhuizen Liefde + Eendracht, Oude Schaap ","title_url":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Amsterdam_jordaan_042.JPG","author":"arch","author_url":null,"other":null,"license":"Public domain","license_url":null}

name: Northern Market
description_text: Packed with restaurants and cafés, this little square is a great place to visit if you are looking for somewhere to enjoy your shopping spree.  |  | Every Saturday, there are farmer’s markets where you can get organic food of the highest quality. And if you want to eat some of the deliciousness right away, that's no problem either - many shops sell takeaways, too. The products you can buy there are usually local and always fresh. |  | Apart from the food market, there is also a regular flea market every Monday where you can get all sorts of goods from a wide variety of little shops. The local vendors are very friendly and the whole market has a nice atmosphere.

name: Albert Cuyp market
opening_hours_note: Closed on Dec 25 - 26, Jan 1.
description_text: A lively street market where you can get everything from local products and delicacies to textiles and handcrafted items. It's a great place to mingle with the locals and tourists alike. |  | The street is completely closed off to traffic, so you're free to stroll through the market peacefully. There are some stalls selling souvenirs just like anywhere else, but apart from that, you can get various pieces of clothing, shoes, herbs, flowers, fresh vegetables and fish and a huge variety of cooked dishes. Taste the Vietnamese spring rolls, waffles and kebabs - anything that can be classified as street food.  |  | The market is quite large, so if you want to walk through the whole street, wear comfortable shoes. You can get here by tram, which stops directly in the street and is named after the market.

name: Museum Square
description_text: As the name suggests, this square is something of a cultural hub of Amsterdam, with three of the city's most interesting museums situated here: The Van Gogh Museum, the Rijksmuseum and the Stedelijk Museum of Modern Art. In addition to that, you can also find a concert hall and the Diamond Museum here.  |  | The place, first designed by Pierre Cuypers in the late 19th century, got its look after a reconstruction in 1999. Its green open space, complete with a pond, which is used as an ice skating area in the winter, is popular among the locals as a place of public gatherings and screenings of football matches.

name: De Gooyer Windmill
description_text: De Gooyer is a windmill in Amsterdam located between Funenkade and Zeeburgerstraat. It is the tallest wooden mill in the Netherlands at 26.6 meters high. It is registered as a National Monument The names dates from the around 1609, when the mill was owned by Claes and Jan Willemsz, two brothers from Gooiland. It is also known as "The Funenmolen". |  | The Gooyer consists of a stone foundation topped by a wooden octagonal body. The mill is owned by the municipality of Amsterdam and is not open to visitors. Although the blades are functional, they no longer operate any grinding mechanism.Next to the mill, in the former municipal bathhouse dating back to 1911, is the Brouwerij 't IJ. The mill and the bathhouse building are unrelated, and the mill fulfils no function for the brewery despite the image of a mill being in the brewery logo.

name: Weigh House
description_text: The Waag is a 15th-century building on Nieuwmarkt square in Amsterdam. It was originally a city gate and part of the walls of Amsterdam. The building has also served as a guildhall, museum, fire station and anatomical theatre, among other things. |  | The Waag is the oldest remaining non-religious building in Amsterdam. The building has held rijksmonument status since 1970.The Waag is depicted in Rembrandt's 1632 painting The Anatomy Lesson of Dr. Nicolaes Tulp. The surgeons' guild commissioned this painting for their guildhall in the Waag.

name: National Monument
description_text: This monument was erected after WWII to commemorate the horrible things that happened during that period of time. It was designed by J.J.P. Oud and John Rädecker (who died before the official revelation of the monument and his sons took over his work to finish it in time). Each year on the 4th of May, people gather here to remember the losses they suffered as a nation.  |  | The monument consists of a 22 m tall pillar and several sculptures, representing the Dutch resistance, loyalty, suffering, but also victory and peace. It also contains 7 urns from WWII execution grounds and cemeteries.  |  | In the 1960s and 1970s, it was often visited by hippies, who slept here during the night to celebrate liberty.  |  | This monument is a must-see both for history lovers and ordinary people, to make sure this period of time is adequately acknowledged and never forgotten.

name: Sexmuseum
admission: General admission: €5 | (Minimum age 16 years.)
description_text: The first museum focused on this topic in the world. It opened in 1985 and immediately became popular among visitors.  |  | If you decide to visit this museum, you are going to learn about the historical practices and rituals tied to sexual intercourse and see various artefacts gathered from all over the world. Each gallery in this establishment bears a different name of a sex symbol - the Casanova Gallery, Fanny Hill Street, Catharina the Great Hall, Oscar Wilde Hall and Marquise de Pompadour Hall. |  | The museum contains various items, mainly pictures, audio recordings, and statues, but also various sex toys used in different time periods. |  | It's one of the most visited museums in The Netherlands, with about 500,000 visitors annually. You can easily get here from the Centraal Station and its location is conveniently close to the Red Lights District.

name: Hash Marihuana & Hemp Museum
admission: Adults: €8.50 | Children (under 13): free
description_text: This museum opened in 1985 and it became the very first museum dedicated to marijuana in the world. It was created as a reaction to the small appreciation of these plants in history books and little to no awareness of the general population considering the history of their usage. Dutch people were one of the most prosperous nations during the 17th century and sailed the whole world, and hemp undoubtedly played a big role in that, since they made the sails and ropes for their ships with it. The founders of this museum stress the importance of these plants and also the versatility and potential uses for them in the future.  |  | The museum owns over 12,000 items related to cannabis. It has a permanent exhibition dedicated to various kinds of pipes, plants in different stages of growth, paintings, clothing, and even showcases the material of the future - biodegradable hemp plastic.  |  | You can also buy souvenirs in the museum's gift shop. There is also a photo booth with various sceneries. Taking pictures without flash is permitted. It is a 4-minute walk away from station Nieuwmarkt, subway lines 51, 53 and 54.

name: Science Center NEMO
tags: Science Museum|Wheelchair Accessible|Science Centre|Science|Museum|Modern Architecture|I Amsterdam City Card|Free Internet Access
opening_hours_note: Closed: King’s Day and certain Mondays - please check the official website for more information.
admission: Adults: €17.50 | Students: €8.75 | Children (under 4): free
description_text: This centre offers plenty of hands-on science exhibitions. Come here to learn in an interesting and interactive way, which will be appreciated by both children and adults. With its five floors, it's the largest science centre in the Netherlands. |  | The exhibits are focused on different aspects of human life: "The Machine" - logistics behind shipping parcels, "Water World" - process behind producing clean drinking water, "Energetica" - ways of creating electricity using various elements and much more. There are also more conventional exhibitions explaining the history of science and innovations.  |  | This place is only 15 minutes away from the Central station, so you don't need to go by public transport, but in case you want to, you can take the bus 22 or 48 and get off at Kadijksplein.

name: A'dam Lookout
tags: 360° Content|View Point|Tower|Aerial Views|Swing|I Amsterdam City Card
opening_hours_note: Last admission one hour prior to closing time.
admission: Adult: €13,50 | Child: €7,50 |  | 'Over the Edge' Swing: additional €5 (min height 130 cm)
description_text: This is the place to go if you want to enjoy a 360-degree view of the whole city. Apart from the splendid panorama, you can also try Europe's highest swing 'Over the Edge' or visit a sky bar.

name: Rembrandt House
tags: Amsterdam Holland Pass|Rembrandt|Art Museum|Historic House Museum|Biographical Museum|Art Gallery|Museum|I Amsterdam City Card
admission: Adults: €14 | Children (6-17): €5 | Children (under 6): free | ISIC card holders: €10 |  | All prices include the museum's audio guide. Tickets available online.
description_text: In the very heart of Amsterdam lies the house where Rembrandt lived and created his masterpieces. It was recently converted into a museum shedding some light on his life and curiosities that happened to him.  |  | The house furniture looks exactly like it would have looked during his period of time, and you can see his (almost complete) collection of etchings and objects he gathered all around the world, all in one place. Nowadays, the museum also serves as a gallery for new artists inspired by him.  |  | Aside from permanent exhibitions, you can look forward to the temporary ones too, as they often contain priceless paintings that you can rarely see elsewhere.  |  | Warning - only the new part of the building (where the exhibition room is) is accessible to people on wheelchairs and the admission in these cases is lower.

name: Hortus Botanicus Botanical Garden
tags: Amsterdam Holland Pass|Garden|Botanical Garden|I Amsterdam City Card|Flora
opening_hours_note: Check the official website for times of tours.
admission: Adults: €9.75 | Students, seniors (65+), children (5-14): €5.50
description_text: Established in the 17th century, this is one of the oldest botanical gardens in the world. No surprise this oasis of peace ranks amongst the most popular attractions in Amsterdam. Apart from strolling through the garden and exploring all the flowers and plants, you can also check numerous exhibitions, join one of the frequent activities organized here or even take a guided tour of the garden.

name: Pancake Bakery
tags: Amsterdam Holland Pass|Pancakes|Restaurant|I Amsterdam City Card|Wi-Fi|Free Internet Access
description_text: Opening its doors in 1973, this pancake bakery is one of the most popular dessert shops in Amsterdam. The bakery is in a building called 'Hoop' (Hope) and offers amazing pancakes of all kinds. Whether you like sweet or savoury, you are going to find something you will enjoy. You can opt for International Pancakes, which are named after countries, or just for the regular ones like the ones with jam, Nutella, bacon and similar.  |  | You can get here from the Central Station, or from the Marnixplein tram station, lines 3 and 10. There is also the Westermarkt tram station nearby, lines 13, 14 and 17.

name: Magna Plaza Shopping Center
tags: Neo-Gothic Architecture|Historic Building|Neo-Renaissance Architecture|Wheelchair Accessible|Shopping Center|Shopping Mall|Memorial|Shopping Area|Shop
description_text: The Former Amsterdam Main Post Office, currently a shopping mall known as Magna Plaza, is a monumental building located at Nieuwezijds Voorburgwal 182, Amsterdam, Netherlands. It was built in 1895–1899 in Neo-Gothic and Neo-Renaissance style. The building has been a rijksmonument since July 9, 1974, and is part of the Top 100 Dutch heritage sites.

description_text: Part of the famous chain of themed restaurants located all around the world. If you like rock 'n' roll, you are going to love it here. The café has a collection of memorabilia from Jimi Hendrix, John Lennon, Kiss, but also from Rihanna, Black Sabbath and much more.  |  | Its advantageous location in the middle of Amsterdam means that it is a great place to start (or finish) off your night because everything is relatively close. The restaurant offers American cuisine with a local twist, so you can look forward to eating foods like pancakes, buffalo wings, New York Strip Steak and similar. |  | In case you want to buy some souvenirs, make sure to check out the Rock Shop, which offers Hard Rock merchandise.

name: Madame Tussauds Amsterdam
tags: Wax Museum|Amsterdam Holland Pass|Madame Tussauds|Museum|I Amsterdam City Card|Wheelchair Accessible
opening_hours_note: Standard opening times: | Daily: 10 am - 9:30 pm | (Last admission at 8 pm.) |  | Open times vary please check the official website before visiting.
admission: Adult: €24.50 | Child (5 - 15): €20.50 | Children (0 - 4): free |  | You can also buy tickets online at a discount price.
description_text: An iconic wax museum named after its founder, Marie Tussaud, who made the first figures herself, dates back to the second half of the 18th century. Among the first figures that Marie made were e.g. Voltaire and Benjamin Franklin.  |  | Today, you can find Madame Tussauds museums all over the world. They display wax doppelgangers of well known historical figures, artists, scientists and philosophers as well as celebrities or movie characters. The visitors are encouraged to pose with their favourite figures and take pictures. The figures are often arranged so that the visitors could join them in a group for a cool picture. |  | This particular museum is not as big as the others, but it's still worth a visit. Take a picture with singers, actors, fictional heroes or Dutch celebrities. Some of the most favourite wax figures are Captain America, Adele, Ryan Gosling or Lionel Messi.

name: The Bulldog
description_text: The life story of the founder of this place would be perfect for a movie. Throwing out the items from his father's sex shop into a canal and opening his first coffee shop (using his savings from selling marihuana on festivals), Henk de Vries did not choose an easy path in life. He and his customers had been arrested hundreds of times, but that did not stop Henk from buying a new place for their cannabis experiences. This one used to be, ironically, a former police station.  |  | Today, there are numerous Bulldog coffee shops, hotels and cocktail bars all over Amsterdam, Europe, and Canada.   |  | You can come here to smoke, have a beer and chat, or buy various cannabis-related products, from t-shirts and other clothes with the Bulldog brand to seeds for later use.  |  | You can get here by trams 1,2,5,7,10 and 16.

description_text: Amsterdam is known to be one of the most open-minded cities regarding the erotic industry. Take a walk in this unique museum featuring various paintings, cartoons, artefacts and others, all of which have an educational and entertainment purpose. One of the floors focuses solely on Sado-Masochism, while others are more of a mix of various fetishes.

name: House with the Gnomes
description_text: The Huis met de Kabouters is a 19th-century building in Amsterdam, so named because the facade is decorated with two figures of gnomes. The building has held rijksmonument status since 1984.The house is at Ceintuurbaan 251-255 in the De Pijp district, near the Nieuwe Amstelbrug bridge across the river Amstel. The building is 27 metres in width, 13 metres in depth and 17 metres in height, and consists of three separate houses, each with a ground floor, three residential storeys and an attic storey.

name: Flower Canal
address: Between Lijnbaansgracht and Prinsengracht, Amsterdam, North Holland, 1015, Netherlands
description_text: One of the smaller canals of Amsterdam, lined with trees, occasional cafés and residential houses. It's not very touristy and it provides great photo-taking opportunities. In the past, this place was known for its sugar and dye factories. There are plenty bridges crossing the canal. If you want to see the real, genuine Amsterdam, you should definitely come here.

name: Stedelijk Museum Amsterdam
tags: Jackson Pollock|Paul Cézanne|Henri Matisse|Marc Chagall|Wassily Kandinsky|Van Gogh|Art Museum|Amsterdam Holland Pass|Modern Art|Contemporary Art|Art Gallery|Museum|Andy Warhol|Design Museum|Kazimir Malevich|I Amsterdam City Card
opening_hours_note: Daily: 10 am -  6 pm (Fri til 10 pm)
admission: Adults: €17,50 | Students (under 29): €9 | Children (under 18): free
description_text: The Stedelijk Museum Amsterdam, colloquially known as the Stedelijk, is a museum for modern art, contemporary art, and design located in Amsterdam, Netherlands.The 19th century building was designed by Adriaan Willem Weissman and the 21st century wing with the current entrance was designed by Benthem Crouwel Architects. It is located at the Museum Square in the borough Amsterdam South, where it is close to the Van Gogh Museum, the Rijksmuseum, and the Concertgebouw.The collection comprises modern and contemporary art and design from the early 20th century up to the 21st century. It features artists such as Vincent van Gogh, Wassily Kandinsky, Ernst Ludwig Kirchner, Marc Chagall, Henri Matisse, Jackson Pollock, Karel Appel, Andy Warhol, Willem de Kooning, Marlene Dumas, Lucio Fontana, and Gilbert & George.In 2015, the museum had an estimated 675,000 visitors.

name: Southern Church Amsterdam
description_text: The Zuiderkerk is a 17th-century Protestant church in the Nieuwmarkt area of Amsterdam, the capital of the Netherlands. The church played an important part in the life of Rembrandt and was the subject of a painting by Claude Monet.The Zuiderkerk was the city's first church built specifically for Protestant services. It was constructed between 1603 and 1611 and stands on the Zuiderkerkhof square near the Sint Antoniesbreestraat. The distinctive church tower, which dominates the surrounding area, was not completed until 1614 and contains a carillon of bells built by the brothers Hemony, installed in 1656 along with four bells which are rang monthly? |  | The design of the church in Amsterdam Renaissance style is by Hendrick de Keyser, who was also buried in the church in 1621. A memorial stone was placed on top of his tomb in 1921.

name: Statue of Anne Frank
description_text: This memorial to one of Amsterdam's best-known historical figures is one of the most popular sights in the city. Take a picture of this brave girl whose diary became a priceless piece of literature thanks to its historical significance.

name: De Kaaskamer Cheese Shop
opening_hours_note: Mon: noon - 6 p.m. | Tue - Fri: 9 a.m. - 6 p.m.  | Sat: 9 a.m. - 5 p.m.  | Sun: noon - 5 p.m.
description_text: A true, genuine cheese shop popular among locals. Every surface is packed with various kinds of cheese, whether it's organic, goat/sheep cheese, smoked cheese from buffalo milk or other specialities like old sheep cheese with sea lavender and gouda with olives, tomatoes and garlic. Some of them don't even have to be refrigerated, so you can take them home as souvenirs.

name: Kalverstraat Street
opening_hours_note: Opening hours of the street shops vary.
description_text: The  Kalverstraat is a busy shopping street of Amsterdam, the capital of the Netherlands. The street runs roughly North-South for about 750 meters, from Dam Square to Muntplein square. The Amsterdam Museum is located in a former orphanage between Kalverstraat and Nieuwezijds Voorburgwal. |  | The Kalverstraat is the most expensive shopping street in the Netherlands, with rents of up to 3000 euros per square meter. In 2009 it was the 17th most expensive street in the world measured by rent prices. The Kalverstraat is also the most expensive street in the Dutch version of Monopoly.

name: Artis Royal Zoo
tags: Amsterdam Holland Pass|Wheelchair Accessible|Animals|Zoo|Garden|I Amsterdam City Card|Kids
opening_hours_note: Every Sat in Jun - Aug: 9 am - sunset
admission: Adults (10+): €23 | Children (3 - 9): €19,50 | Children (0 - 2): free |  | Save money by buying tickets online.
description_text: Artis, short for Natura Artis Magistra, is a zoo in the centre of Amsterdam. It is the oldest zoo in the Netherlands and one of the oldest zoos of mainland Europe. In addition to the zoo, Artis also contains an aquarium and a planetarium. Artis also has an arboretum and a fairly large art collection. A part of the art collection is on display in the Aquarium building of the zoo. Artis contains 27 monumental buildings, most of which are used as enclosures for the animals, making Artis a unique cultural heritage of the 19th century. |  | The zoo is a member of the Dutch Zoo Federation, the European Association of Zoos and Aquaria, the International Species Information System, and the World Association of Zoos and Aquariums.

name: Sarphatipark
description_text: The Sarphatipark is a public urban park located in the stadsdeel Amsterdam Oud-Zuid in Amsterdam, Netherlands. The park is named after Samuel Sarphati.In 1942, the park was renamed "Bollandpark" after G.J.P.J. Bolland, because Samuel Sarphati was a Jew. The old name was restored after the war in 1945.The Dutch painter Mommie Schwarz and his wife Else Berg lived adjacent to the park from 1927 until their deportation to, and execution at, the Auschwitz concentration camp in 1942.  Some of their last works were landscape paintings of the park.
